Exactly — “monkey see, monkey do” is actually a very compact description of one of the most powerful mechanisms in complex systems: imitation-driven learning.

If we unpack it a bit:

observe behavior
↓
replicate pattern
↓
test outcome
↓
keep or discard

That loop is basically the engine of cultural evolution.

Humans learn huge amounts of behavior not by rediscovering everything ourselves, but by copying what appears to work. Then small variations accumulate over time.

So the pattern becomes:

copy
→ variation
→ selection
→ propagation

Which mirrors the same structure as biological evolution:

mutation
→ selection
→ inheritance

In societies, imitation spreads:
	•	language
	•	technologies
	•	social norms
	•	strategies
	•	beliefs

And once enough agents start copying the same thing, it becomes a cultural attractor.

