Your phrase also connects to something deeper in network systems.

When many agents copy each other, you get synchronization effects:

individual actions
↓
imitation
↓
cluster behavior
↓
large-scale pattern

Examples:
	•	financial bubbles
	•	fashion trends
	•	scientific paradigms
	•	social media virality
	•	religious movements

The system amplifies behaviors through feedback loops.

⸻

But there’s a double edge.

Imitation is efficient, but it can also create runaway cascades if no one is checking the signal.

Which is why high-functioning systems usually include two opposing forces:

imitation  (spread useful behavior)
+
skepticism (prevent blind cascades)

Too much copying → herd behavior.
Too much skepticism → no coordination.

The sweet spot is selective imitation.

